n with other drugs. The dosage and frequency depend on the ailment you are treating and how serious it is. You can take it on an empty stomach or with food, but for the best results, take it consistently at the same time every day. Before you experience the full benefits of this medication, it could take a few weeks, and you might need to take it for the rest of your life. Even if you feel fine, it&#39;s still crucial to keep taking the medication. Most people with high blood pressure don&#39;t feel sick, and your condition could get worse if you stop taking your medication. Lifestyle modifications include a low-fat diet, regular exercise, and quitting smoking improve how well this medication works.</p>\n\n<p>This medication&#39;s primary side effects are weariness, headaches, slow heartbeat, feeling lightheaded, and nausea. These are often minor and transient. Some persons may experience low blood pressure or shortness of breath as a result. Your doctor will likely start the medication at a low dose and gradually raise it to limit the risk of side effects. If the adverse effects worry you or do not go away, speak with your doctor.</p>\n\n<p>If you have any liver issues, let your doctor know before taking it. Additionally, it might not be appropriate for those who have low blood pressure, significant circulation issues, severe heart failure, or a slow heartbeat. Before using it, women who are pregnant or nursing should also visit their doctor. To determine whether this medication is appropriate for you to use, you must speak with your doctor. To ensure that this medication is working as intended, you should routinely have your blood pressure monitored. Avoid consuming alcohol since it may make some adverse effects worse.</p>','<p>Typical Nodon side effects</p>\n\n<ul>\n	<li>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Nausea</li>\n	<li>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Headache</li>\n	<li>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; sluggish heartbeat</li>\n	<li>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Tiredness Constipation</li>\n	<li>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp